{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:32:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:32:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12453"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12453"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.05,0.36,0.13,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4961"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46574"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4961"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31490"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2247"},{"type":"tags","id":"2286"},{"type":"tags","id":"2473"},{"type":"tags","id":"2496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44379"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46574"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a six day history of chest pain and increasing difficulty breathing. His history includes congestive heart failure and type 2 diabetes mellitus. He had a 15-pack-year smoking history but quit two years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 136/90 mmHg, pulse 88/min, temperature 37.9 C and respiratory rate 22/min. On percussion of his chest there is dullness at the left lung base with decreased breath sounds on auscultation. A chest X-ray is performed (Image). A diagnostic tap obtains straw-coloured fluid with a pH of 7.3, protein to serum protein ratio of 0.7 and LDH levels of 500 U/L and no organisms were identified. Laboratory investigations show leukocytosis with neutrophilia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antibiotics","Pleurodesis","Therapeutic thoracocentesis","Furosemide","Tube thoracotomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with a left-sided pleural effusion. It could be secondary to congestive heart failure but the pleural fluid protein to serum protein ratio of 0.7 suggest it to be exudative in nature in accordance with the Light\u0027s criteria. It states that fluid is exudate if one of the following Light\u2019s criteria is present:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEffusion protein/serum protein ratio greater than 0.5 (present here)\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEffusion lactate dehydrogenase/serum LDH ratio greater than 0.6\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEffusion LDH level greater than two-thirds the upper limit of the laboratory\u0027s reference range of serum LDH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common causes of exudative effusion include pneumonia, tuberculosis, malignancy, autoimmune disorders etc. The presence of fever suggests it to be a parapneumonic effusion. That no organisms were found in the tap suggests that this is a parapneumonic effusion and not an empyema. If organisms had been found, then a tube thoracotomy to drain the empyema would have been more appropriate. Treating the pneumonia timely with adequate \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would secondarily resolve the effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe role of \u003Cstrong\u003Etherapeutic thoracocentesis (\u003C/strong\u003Einserting a needle or catheter through the chest wall and into the pleural space to drain the accumulated fluid)\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis in complicated parapneumonic effusion. The criteria for complicated effusion include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efrankly purulent fluid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ea pleural fluid pH of less than 7.0-7.1\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eloculated effusions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELDH levels\u0026gt; 1000 U/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebacteria on Gram stain or culture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENone of the above has been mentioned in the case, suggesting it to be an uncomplicated parapneumonic effusion which would resolve once the pneumonia has been treated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplicated and large parapneumonic effusions not treated by thoracocentesis or empyema require drainage by\u003Cstrong\u003E tube thoracotomy.\u003C/strong\u003E It is also known as chest tube insertion, a procedure in which a flexible tube is inserted through the chest wall and into the pleural space to drain fluid or air that has accumulated around the lung.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleurodesis \u003C/strong\u003Einvolves instilling an irritant into the pleural space to cause inflammatory changes that result in bridging fibrosis between the visceral and parietal pleural surfaces, effectively obliterating the potential pleural space. It is most often used for recurrent malignant effusions, considering the limited life span of the patient and aiming for symptomatic relief and minimizing discomfort. It is not indicated in parapneumonic effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is a loop diuretic used in effusions secondary to congestive heart failure or pulmonary oedema as it reduces fluid overload from body. It has no proven role in the management of parapneumonic effusions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with uncomplicated parapneumonic effusions, antibiotics are the mainstay of treatment."],"references":["Shebl E, Paul M. Parapneumonic Pleural Effusions And Empyema Thoracis. StatPearls [Internet]. 2021 Jan."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31490"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12453"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20688"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20688"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aPPb35aaaM4DvDZhVv4NFqMnFIpriB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aPPb35aaaM4DvDZhVv4NFqMnFIpriB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":558,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31490"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-09T11:32:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-09T11:32:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4961"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46574"}}}